Title: Know Your City No.130 View of hills and part of the Owens Valley aqueduct called the Cascades
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.130 -- This is a river that is a long way from home.  And it has been splashing down this spectacular spillway since 1913.  There's nothing like it in the city.  Yes, it's in the city.  See answer on Page 36, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the Cascades, which tumbles beneath Foothill Blvd. and the Golden State Freeway out beyond San Fernando.  This is Owens River water, pictured at the terminus of the 233-mile Owens River Aqueduct.  It is, of course, a project of the Los Angeles Department of Water and Power and some of that water cascading down there could very well have provided your morning shower.

Title: Know Your City No.131 Entrance and tower of Los Angeles' Wrigley Field on E 42nd Place at Avalon Blvd
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.131 -- Just because a lot of hits have been made here, you might think it is a movie studio.  But it isn't, by gum.  And even if cherubs do cavort here, it isn't heaven, either.  No labor trouble, but plenty of strikes.  See Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: With all those corny clues, you surely were able to guess that the structure shown in the photo is Wrigley Field on E 42nd Place at Avalon Blvd., home of the Los Angeles Angels baseball club.|~|Los Angeles' Wrigley Field was built by William Wrigley Jr. in the 1920s.  The structure was demolished in 1966.

Title: Know Your City No.132 Front entrance of former J.J. Haggarty residence at 3330 W Adams Blvd. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 132 -- Here's one that will stump you.  This unique, castle-like structure is on a prominent thoroughfare.  Once a private residence, it has an interior which matches the exterior for unusual medieval design.  Turn to Page 38, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: This fine old former residence, located at 3330 W Adams Blvd., now serves as headquarters for the Church Federation of Los Angeles.  And, if you guessed this one, you really know you city.|~|The house was built for Los Angeles department store merchant John J. Haggarty.

Title: Know Your City No.133 Four-legged steel girder control tower at Los Angeles International Airport
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.133 -- Just because it supervises a lot of take-offs and oversees several strips doesn’t mean that this is headquarters for a bunch of burlesque queens.  With those clues and the photo hints it should be easy.  If not, see Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: To be perfectly plane about it, the structure in the photo could be nothing else but the control tower at Los Angeles International Airport.  And if you didn't recognize it, you're just not on the beam.

Title: Know Your City No.135 One of the Van Norman Lakes, Owens River Aqueduct reservoir, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.135 -- Los Angeles residents should recognize this.  It is pretty important to their existence.  Its name was changed not too long ago and it became a lake.  But its function is more vital than boating.  See Page 20, Part lA.
Description.note: ANSWER: The body of water shown in the photo is one of the Van Norman Lakes.  Known until recently as the Upper San Fernando Reservoir, it is used by the Los Angeles Department of Water and Power as the main storage place for the precious water from the Owens River, arriving here via a 233-mile aqueduct.  It is adjacent to Sepulveda Blvd. in the northwest corner of the San Fernando Valley.  It and a similar nearby reservoir were renamed in honor of late H.A. Van Norman, once general manager of the Department of Water and Power, who played a leading role in construction of the Owens River Aqueduct.

Title: Know Your City No.137 Sepulveda Dam and a portion of the Sepulveda Flood Control Basin, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 137 -- There are quite a lot of things this isn't: It isn't a race track, it isn't a polo field, and it isn't a stadium.  Matter of fact there is only one thing it IS.  And, if you can guess, you're good.  See answer, Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: What the photo shows is Sepulveda Dam and a portion of the huge Sepulveda Flood Control Basin.  It is situated just west of Sepulveda blvd. and extends between Magnolia and Victory Blvds. In the general vicinity of Van Nuys.

Title: Know Your City No.138 Angled view of entrance of Children's Home Society of California at 3100 W Adams Blvd. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 138 -- These stately columns comprise a corner of a former residence that now is headquarters for a Community Chest agency.  You can't see it, but there's a building in back where babies come and go.  See Page 29, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: It probably wasn't fair to show such a small portion of the place, but this is the Children's Home Society of California, a licensed adoption agency at 3100 W Adams Blvd.  But, the portion that was pictured should have been readily recognized because it faces the busy intersection of W Adams Blvd. and Arlington Ave.|~|CHS was founded in the 1890s by Dr. and Mrs. J. R. Townsend to assist homeless and abandoned children.

Title: Know Your City No.140 Eastern end of Hyperion Ave. Bridge and Victory Memorial, Atwater Village (Los Angeles), 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.140 -- These things keep getting easier and easier.  Surely you recognize this scene.  It isn't a Answer, even if it does have the same name.  See?  Even if it is easy, we keep giving it away.  What is it?  See Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: It's the Hyperion Ave. Bridge that swoops down over Riverside Drive and the section of it shown in the photo is near its eastern end where it intersects with Glendale Blvd. out in the Atwater district.  Sewer?  Well, we have a Hyperion sewer, don't' we?  Admittedly pretty far-fetched, but then...|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #164 by the City of Los Angeles in 1976.

Title: Know Your City No.141 Entrance and façade of old Bimini Hot Springs and Bath Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.141 -- Lots of people used to get all steamed up in this place.  Long closed, it once was world famous and one of the top tourist attractions.  It wasn't a billiard parlor, but there was plenty of pool.  See the answer on Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the entrance to the old Bimini Hot Springs and Bath.  Situated at 180 Bimini Place, just east of Vermont Ave., "Bimini" enjoyed years of great popularity as a health spot-- had mineral baths, steam baths and no less than three swimming pools.|~|Bimini Baths feed by hot mineral springs, 2,000 feet underground was founded by Dr. David W. Edwards in 1902.   The baths closed in the 1950s.  In the 1990s Los Angeles Eco-Village bought the buildings and grounds.

Title: Know Your City No.143 View looking down train tracks at the abandoned Pacific Electric tunnel and hillside Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.143 -- This could be one you'll recognize right away -- or will puzzle you for hours.  Only one in town; used to be a busy place and has had a lot of people temporarily in the dark.  For the answer see Page 36, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Yep, it's the old abandoned Pacific Electric tunnel through which interurban cars used to rumble from Glendale Blvd. to the Subway Terminal.

Title: Know Your City No.147 View from underneath of viaduct and streets at 1st Street and Beverly Blvd. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.147 -- If you can read the numbers on that bus, you've got it made.  It is just possible that viaduct and all those converging streets may confuse you a bit and you won't know what it is.  Answer on Page 30, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: You really should have recognized the scene in the photo because it shows the viaduct where 1st St. becomes Beverly Blvd. and, what's more, shows 2nd St. where IT becomes Glendale Blvd. and, all in all, it's pretty doggone complicated.

Title: Know Your City No.147 Shakespeare Bridge and surrounding homes on Franklin Ave. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.148 -- Now here's one that is going to throw a lot of people.  Of course, it's a bridge.  But what bridge?  And where? Even with the fancy cupolas, it really isn't a very important bridge.  Except to people who cross it.  See Page 7, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: This is the nice little bridge that carries Franklin Ave. in 3800 block out Los Feliz way.  What it carries Franklin Ave. over is not much more than a weedy little gulch.  But it's handy.|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #126 by the City of Los Angeles in 1974.

Title: Know Your City No.150 Front of main building of John Marshall High School in the Los Feliz-Silver Lake district, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.150 -- Well, the young people who occupy this building call themselves Barristers.  They aren't lawyers, but the institution is named after one.  And that should suffice in the hint department.  See Page 37, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: The handsome structure in the photo is the main building of John Marshall High School at 3939 Tracy St., in the Los Feliz-Silver Lake district.  Inasmuch as the school is named after the great Chief Justice it is only natural that its athletic teams are known as the Barristers.

Title: Know Your City No.151 Los Angeles River looking north beneath the 7th St. Bridge toward the 6th St. Bridge.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.151 -- Oh, this is silly.  Of course, it's a river.  And it's foolish to ask which one.  Because how many rivers does Los Angeles have?  So let's just leave it that you're to guess WHERE along the river this is.  Page 19, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Yep, it's the Los Angeles River, all right--Looking north beneath the 7th St. Bridge toward the 6th St. Bridge.  That shiny stuff in the picture, incidentally, is water.

Title: Know Your City No.154 Angled view of front of Ebell Club, at 4400 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 154 -- This is the front of one of the city's foremost centers of culture and education.  Just behind camera is busiest street in town.  In its present location since 1927, it has theater in back.  See Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Although only a small portion of it was shown you should've recognized the Ebell Club, which is at 4400 Wilshire Blvd., corner of Lucerne Blvd.  And we made it easy by mentioning the theater, the Wilshire Ebell Theater, which is at the rear of the premises.|~|The Ebell of Los Angeles is an educational and philanthropic organization founded by women in 1894.  The mission is to participate in and encourage the educational, cultural and social growth of the diverse Los Angeles community.  In honor of Dr.Adrian Ebell.  --From Ebell of Los Angeles mission statement.  Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #250 by the City of Los Angeles in 1982.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.155 -- Through these portals pass some of the city's top citizens.  Inside posts, very private.  Outside, very public.  Answer Page 8, Part2.
Description.note: ANSWER: The imposing pillars in the pictures is the entrance from Wilshire Blvd. (at the intersection of Rossmore Ave.) to Fremont Place, one of the city's most exclusive residential districts.

Title: Know Your City No.157 St. Angelo Hotel at 237 N Grand Ave. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.157 -- Take a good look, because this old landmark, since 1887, won't be around much longer.  Thousands pass it daily.  Many will recognize it, but they'll be darned if they remember where it is.  See Page 6, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the old St. Angelo Hotel at 237 N Grand Ave., just off Temple St. Now , do you remember?  Anyway, it was recently ordered vacated by the Board of Health and soon will be torn down.  And so another famous old landmark will live only in the photo files.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.167 -- It borders on ridiculous to imagine that there's anyone in town who won't recognize this building.  But, just in case, the photographer picked a foreground that makes it a dead giveaway.  Not much point in turning to Page 32, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The modern structure in the photo could be northing else, of course, but the Mirror Building at 2nd and Spring Sts. And, while artistically symbolic, those rolls of newsprint in the foreground eliminated any possible guesswork.

Title: Know Your City No.171 Murals at the entrance of Los Angeles County General Hospital
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.171 -- Although thousands of people pass beneath these colorful and impressive murals, chances are that few will know where they are.  Hint: this ceiling has something to do with healing.  A well-known figure is seen at top center, right.  To learn the correct answer, turn to Page 30, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: The tridomed murals are in the portlier of the main entrance to the General Hospital.  And there may be those who recognized the portrait in right upper center (the one being held by the young child) as that of Hippocrates, the Greek physician so revered by the medical profession.|~|The murals were created in 1932.

Title: Know Your City No.172 Los Angeles City Jail building and surrounding grounds in 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.172 -- This isn’t a watch factory, although a lot of time made here.  And the Communists wish they had so many cells.  Even if this is seldom-seen angle, you surely can guess after those hints.  See Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Just to let down the bars and tell you, the building in the photo is the City Jail.  The picture was taken from Elysian Park Drive on the west side of the Los Angeles River.

Title: Know Your City No.173 Southbound lanes of Pasadena Freeway going through Elysian Park, Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.173 -- Told you yesterday you wouldn't get any clues with today's photo.  Heavens, you shouldn't need them because everyone certainly must recognize this scene.  If you really must know, turn to Page 33, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Naturally, it is the Pasadena Freeway as it zips through Elysian Park.  Photo was made from the Park Row Drive overpass, looking south high above the inbound lanes.  Obvious postscript: It was NOT made during the rush hour.

Title: Know Your City No.181 Empty beach and walkway at Venice Beach, Calif. looking south toward Playa del Rey
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.181 -- No, this isn't the edge of the Sahara, despite all the sand, palm tress and those oil wells in the distance.  It's within the city limits, which contain few stretches of sand like this.  For the answer, see Page 32, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Now that you think of it, the beach shown in the photo is the broad expanse of the municipal beach at Venice, looking south toward Playa del Rey.  That horizontal black line in center of the picture is the Pacific Ocean.  What the photo lacks: Bathing beauties.

Title: Know Your City No.182 Statues of saber-tooth tigers at La Brea Tar Pits Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.182 -- Hold that tiiiger!  Determined to beat the tar out of each other, these two animals are putting the bite on each other in a historic spot that is near a busy boulevard.  If that isn't enough, see Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: This statue of a couple of unfriendly saber-tooth tigers is in the famous La Brea Pits in Hancock Park on Wilshire Blvd.  That pool of smooth black stuff behind them is one of the eeringly bubbling pits of fossil-bearing asphalt deposits of the Pleistocene Epoch. (Got all that from a card tacked up on the fence.)|~|The sculpture was created by Hermann T. Beck, based on drawings by Joseph L. Roop.

Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the main entrance and a portion of the Times Boys Club at 2635 Pasadena Ave.  As we said, many appreciate it, but few-other than the lucky kids who belong to it- would receives most of the benefits from the traditional Los Angeles Rams vs. Washington Redskins professional football game every August.

Title: Know Your City No.197 Memorial for firemen of the Los Angeles Fire Department
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.197 -- Of course, you will recognize this as a memorial.  But, what and where is it?  Hint: Although the trees obscure any definite clues, it is in a very prominent spot of the city. If you can't guess, take a peek at Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The monument was erected in memoriam "to the fighting men of the Fire Department, city of Los Angeles, who met violent death while in performance of their duties."  It stands in the little park on the south side of the City Hall, near the intersection of 1st and Spring Sts., and was dedicated Oct. 14, 1944.

Title: Know Your City No.198; Cityscape view looking north from the City Hall tower Los Angeles, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.198 -- How lazy can you get? Sure, this is a bird's-eye view of the city.  Sure, it was shot from the City Hall tower.  All you have to figure out is which way camera was pointing.  Easy? Some will miss.  See Page 20, Part 1A.
Description.note: ANSWER: There were a million landmarks to tell you that the camera was pointed north from the City Hall tower.  In the foreground are the top of the Federal Building and the Hollywood-Santa Ana Freeway.  Off to the right are the clump of trees that is the Plaza and beyond it the Post Office Terminal Annex.  At the extreme left N Broadway heads toward the tree-covered hills of Elysian Park.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.199 -- Here's the second of four directional views of the city taken from the City Hall tower.  And, like all of them, you should have no trouble figuring out which way the camera pointed.  Too easy?  See Page 36, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: East.  That's the view from the City Hall tower.  In the foreground the top of the new Police Administration Building.  At lower right the intersection of 1st and San Pedro Sts.  Slanting across the photo just above center the Los Angeles River.  Three bridges are visible--1st St., 4th St. and 6th St.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.200 -- Well, here we are at the 200 mark in this [series].  And, without trying to be cute about it, this picture taken from the City Hall tower is, if nothing else, symbolic of the whole idea.  Of course, you know direction camera is facing.  Don't fret, series is going to continue.  See Page 34, Part [?].
Description.note: ANSWER: The photo, looking south by west from the City Hall tower, is a panorama of the downtown business district.  And, of course, it wasn't expected to baffle anybody.  Too many prominent landmarks, including the Times and Mirror Buildings in center foreground.

Title: Know Your City No.201; Cityscape view looking west from the City Hall tower in Los Angeles, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.201 -- Maybe this view from City Hall tower wasn't such a hot idea after all.  Too easy.  This one should be, if only because the other three already have been published.  That leaves you one choice.  See Page 35, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: West. That's the way you were looking in the photo from the City Hall tower.  That's the roof of the Hall of Records in the foreground.  Over at the left is the Law Building and steel structure for the new County Courthouse.  Beyond Temple St. at the right it the four-level interchange of the freeways and, way at the left, Beverly Blvd. goes over Belmont Hill.  Hollywood and the Hollywood Hills are out there in the haze somewhere.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.203 -- Nope, this isn't part of Disneyland.  And it isn’t in jolly old England, either.  It is right here in Los Angeles and fronts on one of our busier thoroughfare.  A unique residence.  Find the answer on Page 29, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: This "Castle of Enchantment," as the tablet in the entrance arch identifies it, is the unusual home, created by themselves, of Milton and Josie Hopkins.  It is at 4857 Melrose Ave., just east of Western Ave.

Description.note: ANSWER: Dynamiters?  Jewel City? Sure, what else could it be but a section of the handsome Glendale Union High School?  Shucks, anybody'd a-knowed that.

Description.note: ANSWER: This is going to be brief because the subject of the photo was so obvious: Sure, it is the Eagle Rock in the Annandale Hills and after which the community farthermost in the northeastern section of Los Angeles' city limits is located.  Dumb remark: It's been there for years.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.215 -- No eggs around this modern building, but you might find an occasional ham.  It is on a very busy street and is brand new, dedicated only last May 25.  If you've seen it, you won't forget.  See Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The eye-catching building is the new headquarters of the Screen Actors Guild at 7750 Sunset Blvd. What else do you need to know?|~|The building at 7750 Sunset Blvd. served as the Screen Actors Guild headquarters from 1956- 1986.

Title: Know Your City No.221 View over fence of buildings of Ramona Convent in Alhambra, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.221 -- Standing high on a hill and dominating surrounding countryside is this famous institution.  It is a familiar sight to Southlanders.  But many may not know of its interesting history.  Answer on Page 30, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is a portion-including its three imposing towers-of the Ramona Convent in Alhambra.  Opened by the Sisters of the Holy Names in 1889, it is the Southland's oldest Catholic school for girls.  This hill upon which it stands and some surrounding property was presented to the Sisters by the Shorb family, which,  at one time, owned most of what is now Alhambra and San Marino.  And the convent is named after one of the Shorb daughters, Ramona, and not, as many presume, after the Spanish girl who became Alessandro's bride.

Description.note: ANSWER: The excellently landscaped establishment in the photo is the Eastern Star Home at 11725 Sunset Blvd. in Brentwood.  Didn't you notice the star atop the entrance tower?  The home, the only one of its kind in California, was built in 1933.

Description.note: ANSWER: Nope, it really isn't Bryce Canyon.  As you possibly suspected, it is none other than an odd-angled shot of one of the stairways leading from the Santa Monica Palisades down to the beach.  Not exactly the best thing we've done…

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.233 -- Pretty doggone picturesque, huh?  If you've ever seen this, you've never forgotten.  If not, give up.  You'll never guess.  If not within the Los Angeles limits, it's close to it.  To shorten the agony, see Page 3, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: The photo shows only a portion of one of the most unusual and picturesque places in the Los Angeles area - Lake Shrine of the Self Realization Federation, 'way out on Sunset Blvd. in the vicinity of Santa Ynez Canyon.  What a field day this place offers photographers!  Or just plain, wide-eyed tourists, for that matter.  Beautiful spot with a strange calmness and where, in a shrine just behind the impressive portal in the photo, is a portion of the ashes of Mahatma Gandhi.|~|Golden Lotus Archway.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.239 -- Its name contains a color.  And it was built with determined hands by one man.  Also, it has the distinction of being open 24 hours a day.  But it's no all-night café. Take a guess.  If no luck, see Page 9, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: As many of you probably knew, the structure in the photo is the famous Little Brown Church in the Valley.  Located at 4418 Coldwater Canyon Ave., North Hollywood, it was built alone by the Rev. John H. Wells, who is still its pastor.  Its doors are never locked.

Description.note: ANSWER: This replica of the great Lincoln Memorial statue, the figure gazing pensively at the flood-channel Los Angeles River, sits strikingly among other castoff properties behind Republic studios out on Ventura Blvd.  The photo was made from the new Colfax Ave. bridge.

Description.note: ANSWER: If you're wondering why these Know Your City photos are getting easier, it's because the series is coasting to the finish.  Going to wind it up Wednesday with No.250. Title: Know Your City No.249 Front porch and marker of Avila Adobe on Olvera Street, Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.249 -- How better to begin the windup of this series than at the beginning.  And that's what you see here--the beginning.  It is probably one of city's most historical structures.  If you don't know the answer, then look on Page 14, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: The structure in the photo is the Avila Adobe, generally conceded to be the oldest building in Los Angeles.  It is located at 14 Olvera Street.  Built in 1818 by Don Francisco Avila, it served as American headquarters in 1847 when U.S. troops captured the city.  It has the further distinction of having flown four flags--Spanish, Mexican, the California Republic, and the Stars and Stripes.  And, as Consuela de Bonzo, "Queen" of Olvera Street, puts it: "It is the only place in the world around here like that."
